MCF-7 cells were quantitatively analyzed by the proposed fluorescence cytosensor under the optimized experimental conditions. Specifically, fluorescence cytosensors were reacted with MCF-7 cells with different concentrations, and fluorescence signal changed relying on the release of FA@CDs from CoOOH, which was relevant to the quantities of MCF-7 cells in samples (Fig. 4
                        A). The results showed that the fluorescence signal progressively increased by the addition of MCF-7 cells from 10 cells/mL to 105 cells/mL. Meanwhile, the fluorescence signal showed a good linear relationship with the logarithm of the MCF-7 cells concentrations in the calibration plots of Fig. 4B. In this part, the linear regression equation, analyzed to be Y = 500.5 × lg C – 107.5 (Y: fluorescence intensity; C: concentration of MCF-7 cells), possessed the linear correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) of 0.9915 and the limit of detection was calculated as 5 cells/mL (S/N = 3). Compared with other aptamers-based cytosensors for MCF-7 cells detection, both wider linear range and lower detection limit were reached in this developed strategy (Table S1), which might be mainly due to the separation and enrichment of Apt@MBs as well as the superior amplification signal ability of the CDs/CoOOH.

We tested analytes in white blood cells (WBC) samples to demonstrate the performance of the developed fluorescence cytosensor for detecting MCF-7 cells in a complicated biological environment. Simply, MCF-7 cells of various concentrations were added into WBC with the concentration of 105 cells/mL and analyzed by the fluorescence cytosensor. As we can see, when the concentrations of MCF-7 cells progressively increased from 50 cells/mL to 105 cells/mL in the mixture samples, the fluorescence signal increased with the increase of target cells (Fig. 5
                        A). Moreover, the linear equation, as Y = 437.5 × lg C – 198.6, had the linear correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) as 0.9922, agreeing with results obtained in the sensitive assay (Fig. 5B). Additionally, the limit of detection of this developed cytosensor for MCF-7 cells detection in WBC sample was as low as 35 cells/mL. These results demonstrated this strategy owned great potential for sensitive and accurate determination of MCF-7 cells in a complicated biological environment.
